@figment1988 That's because Nintendo didn't have anything to do with the development, or the publishing.  They licensed the rights to Philips before their SNES-CD add-on deal fell through.  Had Nintendo stuck with the idea, we would have seen a direct competitor to the SegaCD, but for use with the SNES.

Similar things happen pretty frequently.. such as with the "non-canon" Metal Gear sequel.

However, I think it's become fairly passé to even mention the CD-i, since 99.9% of the people who drone about it have never played it, nor touched a CD-i with their own hands.  It's getting to a point where people who were not alive back then (and those who are too young to remember) should probably just stop talking about it.  Yknow like if you're going to bother making fun of it, you should at least get your facts straight instead of tossing Nintendo under the bus for something they didn't do.
